<main class="content">

  <p>More than half of all Australian adults have not prepared a will. This means that if they died tomorrow, their assets would be distributed according to government intestacy rules — not their wishes.</p>

  <h2>Why Don't People Have Wills?</h2>

  <p>Research consistently shows the same reasons:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Procrastination</strong> — "I'll get around to it eventually"</li>
    <li><strong>Perceived complexity</strong> — "It's too complicated and expensive"</li>
    <li><strong>Discomfort</strong> — "I don't want to think about death"</li>
    <li><strong>Assumptions</strong> — "Everything will just go to my spouse anyway"</li>
    <li><strong>Youth</strong> — "I'm too young to need a will"</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What Happens Without a Will?</h2>

  <p>When someone dies without a will (called dying "intestate"), the state decides who gets what. In Australia, this typically means:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Your spouse may not receive everything — children may be entitled to a share</li>
    <li>De facto partners may need to prove their relationship in court</li>
    <li>Blended families face complicated division rules</li>
    <li>Your preferred executor has no authority — the court appoints an administrator</li>
    <li>Guardianship of minor children is decided by the court, not you</li>
    <li>Charities, friends, or carers you wanted to include receive nothing</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="cta-box">
    <h3>The Real Risk</h3>
    <p>Dying without a will doesn't just create inconvenience — it can cause family conflict, legal costs, and outcomes you never intended. The people you love most may spend months navigating courts instead of grieving.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>What You Can Do</h2>

  <p>Creating a will is simpler than most people think. A basic will can be completed in under an hour. The key is to start — even a simple will is far better than no will at all.</p>

  <p>If your situation involves blended families, significant assets, business interests, or potential disputes, consider getting professional advice to ensure your will is properly structured.</p>

